  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. The penalties can vary based on the specific statutes violated, the amount of money involved, and other factors. Here\u2019s a general overview:\n\n### **Statutes Govern Money Laundering**\n1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** - Prohibits financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activity with the intent to promote illegal activity, conceal the source of funds, or evade taxes.\n2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** - Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property valued at more than $10,000.\n\n### **Criminal Penalties**\n- **Fines**: \n  - Individuals may be fined up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the transaction** (whichever is greater). \n  - Organizations may be fined up to **$1 million** or **twice the value of the transaction** (whichever is greater).\n- **Imprisonment**:\n  - Convictions under \u00a7 1956 can result in up to **20 years** in federal prison.\n  - Convictions under \u00a7 1957 can result in up to **10 years** in federal prison.\n  - If the laundering involves proceeds from drug trafficking or terrorism, penalties can be even more severe.\n\n### **Civil Penalties**\n- Civil fines can be imposed in addition to criminal penalties. These fines can be substantial and may include forfeiture of assets involved in the money laundering scheme.\n\n### **Forfeiture**\n- Assets and property involved in money laundering may be subject to **civil or criminal forfeiture**, meaning the government can seize and take ownership of them.\n\n### **Additional Consequences**\n- A conviction for money laundering can result in a permanent criminal record, affecting employment opportunities, professional licenses, and more.\n- Non-U.S. citizens may face deportation or other immigration consequences.\n\n### **Aggravating Factors**\nPenalties can increase if:\n- The amount of money laundered is particularly large.\n- The laundering involves organized crime, drug trafficking, or terrorism.\n- The defendant has prior criminal convictions.\n\nThese penalties underscore the severity with which federal law treats money laundering offenses. Legal advice from a qualified attorney is essential if facing such charges.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
